segments.text: You had mentioned earlier that when you're on this training phase, when you first got to Tinian, that you didn't actually have your own plane.
That you sort of went up in whatever was loose.
Whatever was available.
Usually the oldest junker over there.
That's right, the one nobody else...
When did you get your own plane?
We got our own plane probably after our eighth mission.
Was that typical?
It just depended on the losses.

Some of the older crews, see we went in as a replacement crew, some of the older crews that were in there, if they weren't assigned to fly the mission and their plane was available, another crew would fly that plane.
If it was lost on the mission, then this older crew didn't have a plane.
Oh, oh.
And they got the next new plane.
So seniority kind of thing.
So seniority.
The next new plane came in, coming in, was theirs.
Okay.
So the system took, in your case, eight missions.
Eight missions.
Before you generated enough seniority to get a plane.
To get a plane.
Did you all personalize your plane in any way?
We didn't name it.
It wasn't painted, right?
It was silver?
No, it was just silver.
Actually, most of the 29s weren't painted, were they?
No, there was no paint on them, just the nose art, if they had any.
When we first went in and they had the coral runways, we'd have to go down occasionally
the whole crew plus the ground crew, and we'd wash them to get that coral off the bottom to reduce the drag on them.

I was wondering about that, how you wash the planes, because the friends I've got who are pilots, they go out and wash planes all the time, maybe little Cessnas and stuff like that, because it really matters with a Cessna.
You can lose 10 miles an hour by having a dirty plane.
And a man with a big old bomber carrying a whole lot of, I mean, you didn't want to lose anything, especially.
But once the runways were paved, that became less of a critical issue?
Not quite as critical.
Because that car road, if the runways were at least a bit damp, it would just stick like cement.
Yeah.
We took one night, we took off, it was probably about two o'clock in the morning or something like that.
Our runways were
a little over 10,000 feet long.
We took off on coral runways and came back 14 hours later and landed on asphalt runways.
Somebody had been busy.
They had worked for months mining this coral, crushing it, getting it all prepared for asphalt.
They had mountains of it.
And when we took off, there was just train after train of the asphalt pavers and the mixes there.
As soon as we all got off the runways, they started in.
Hmm.
Now was this Army engineer guys who did this?
Seabees.
Or Seabees?
Construction battalions?
That's impressive.
And they had lights strung out all along there so they could work at night.
We came back, landed in the daylight, but on a black runway.
You knew that was going to happen.
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, they were all.
Is this the right island?
They were all out there strung out along the runways as we were taking off.
Yeah.
And the coral was probably a light color, right?
Oh, yeah, it was white.
Yeah.
Glare off of it.
In fact, the first time we landed on a coral runway,
It was a quadulant.
And the pilots really bounced it in there.
Couldn't find it.
Because of the glare coming up off of it.
They weren't used to anything that bright.
And it put some flat spots on the wheels.
Yeah, I'll bet.
I'll bet.
How long, or you probably wouldn't even necessarily know this, but how long did those tires last?
Seems like they'd be a tremendous amount of wear.
Many of those, reading that book, a lot of those planes took off way over their low level.
Oh, yeah, way, way.
And I was thinking, you know, coming back, you know, you could just stray around.
It goes, I mean, you'll get a flat tire or something.
I mean, there could be some serious stresses and strains on the, not just the gear, but the tires themselves.
We never lost a tire.
In fact, that landing at Kwajalein, which we,
He bounced him and then came in, came back down for the second landing.
He had put the brakes on and tried to hit it that first and it just went up and came back down.
The wheels weren't turning when he landed and it kind of skidded for a while and wore some black spot.
And those tires were changed out.
But other than that, we didn't ourselves experience any difficulties with tires.
But of course, it was a problem.
Yeah.
Was that, do you think that was sort of a function of pilot skill, maybe?
You mean like our instance?
Yeah.
Well, it was just something new.
They had never flown in that type of conditions before.
That's not what I meant.
What I meant was the fact that you didn't have any problems with your tires.
Well, it was just we didn't get hit.
We didn't get any anti-aircraft fire or any bullets through or anything that damaged one.
And the pilots, usually the pilots
They were pretty smooth landings.
That was our two oldest crew members.
What kind of rank were the pilots?
Were they captains, majors?
One was a captain, one was first lieutenant.
Both of them had been infantry officers and transferred out of the infantry and went to pilot training school.
And the airplane commander,
who was the captain, had been in the training command for a while.
Once he finished pilot training, he stayed in the training command and was training pilots in multi-engine stuff.
You mentioned also that after 15 missions, you went back to the States to go to lead crew school.
What was the significance of the 15 missions?
A tour of duty was 35 missions.
If you were selected for a lead crew, they didn't want you using up those missions that you had remaining on your tour.
When you came back, you still had 20 missions that you could fly as a lead crew.

so once we hit the it was just an arbitrary figure uh that they had selected at that time uh crews to go back to lead crew school they could envision that down the line some of the the pilots that were flying leading the formations in and so forth were nearing a tour of duty they needed replacements yeah there's a perpetual contract perpetual thing and uh
Our crew was selected to become a lead crew.
But not everyone was, is that right?
No.
I mean that said something about your crew I would think.
Something positive.
It was a positive action on our, we took it to be very positive that we were well regarded.
Where did you go to lead crew school?
Muroc.
Oh really?
On the dry lake?
Dry lake.
It's Edwards Air Force Base now, isn't it?
Yeah.
But we went each crew there at Muroc.
And while we were there was when they dropped the atomic bombs.
So you never actually went back?
So then we were traveling under Class A priority.
And after the Japanese surrendered, they went under our priorities because of military government personnel going to Japan.
had a higher priority than me.
So what happened after that?
Did you ever get back to the Pacific?
No.
We went to Sacramento.
Hamilton Field and stayed there for about a month.
Three weeks to a month.
While they were, the powers that be were trying to decide what to do with us.
So they finally sent us to separation centers.
Where'd you send them?
Lackland.
Oh, really?
They sent you to the one nearest your home.
So I went to Lackland.
And when was this?
This was in, was it still 45?
So you got out in the fall, I guess?
I got out in, let's see, that was in.
Bombs were dropped in August.
Surrender was September.
I got out actually in October.
Oh, that's pretty quick.
And had final, I had a leave up, well into December.
So you got paid through up into December.
Okay.
The entire time that I was in the service, I never had a leave.
It was always from one school to the next,
I did get home.
Well, you were in for two years, though.
A little over two years, about two and a half.
Nearly two and a half years.
So there was some accumulated leave.
And you got out as a one lieutenant?
First lieutenant, yeah.
Did you stay in the reserves or anything after you got out?
I stayed in the reserves.
Got called up in Korea.
No, are you kidding?
and went to Randolph Field.
And because I had flown in B-29s and they were training crews on B-29s, I stayed there as an instructor for 19 months and then got out.
I got out of the reserves.
I got enough of that.
What were you by the time you got out of that?
You probably got promoted again.
No.
You didn't sell a first lieutenant.
Because I wasn't staying in.
Oh.
They knew when the 19 months was up that I was gone.
Well, that's interesting.
So when you separated, you went back to A&M.
In January of 46.
And decided.
You didn't want electrical engineering anymore.
You got into architecture.
Yeah.
I went down beforehand and talked to Mr. Langford.
He okayed the transfer over into the architecture department.
Now you graduated in 40...
I got out in January of 49.
49, okay.
And what did you do then?
Before you got back in the green water.
Well, I came to Dallas and went to work for a construction company.
Starting out in the office as an estimator.
Going over the plans and working as an estimator.
And then we got
a job in Oak Ridge, Tennessee.
You mean as a contractor?
As a contractor.
And guess who he met there?
Out on the town site.
I was going to get to that.
And so I went out there as the field engineer.
It was a housing project.
For the scientists and what have you?
Some of it, it was completely on township.
The government owned it all then.
And the facilities were assigned.
I don't know how they went about assigning who lived where, but we had about
Well, we had two housing projects there.
One of them was some little duplexes, which at the time were set up as colored housing.
That was before the days of any integration, even in the government ranks.
And then the others were apartment buildings and some row houses.
In total, we were probably building 1,100 units or something like that.
So you were up there for quite a while.
Well, I was up.
Would have been there for quite a while, but actually I was up.
Because you got snatched away.
So well, yeah, if you left A&M in January of 49,
You were a big 25 years of age, still a young man.
You got a job as a contractor.
Is the contractor still in business?
No.
He's dead now.
Man, Laverne.
Then you went to Tennessee.
When did you meet Betty?
In Tennessee.
I mean, was that before you went to this Korea thing at Randolph or wherever?
when we married just before I left our service.
How'd you meet her?
I didn't.
It was a blind date.
We knew each other approximately four months when we were married.
It was really a blind date?
And 46 years later, there we are.
Oh, you're a lonely guy, out of town, right?
And you got married just before you got yanked back into the service?
Well, I got the call to come to report for duty.
What was that, 1950?
And y'all got married in Tennessee?
In August and came to Texas.
In August?
In August.
I thought I'd died and gone to hell.
At Texas City.
Texas City, oh, that's great.
Well, you just missed the explosion.
Texas City.
Just after?
Yeah, the town blew up in 48, 49, something like that.
This was 50.
Built back.
No, I stationed at Ellington Field for a month.
Refresher course.
And then went from there to Randolph.
So you got to accompany your husband.
Mm-hmm.
Randolph wasn't bad.
No, Randolph wasn't bad.
Ellington could have been nasty.
It was that odor in Texas City and the mosquitoes.
And a little gal from the hills of Tennessee had never experienced that before.
Yeah, because they've got mosquitoes you can track on radar.
Oh, Lord.
Our walls were red.
No air conditioning.
That was the only place where we could find any place to stay.
Military personnel that are going to be there for a month, it's hard to find an apartment.
This one real estate agent called
to Texas City and there was this one guy had got called up, recalled in the Marine Corps.
And he had no objections to it.
Military personnel using, it was actually a row house.
A little one bedroom row house.
And the shoes and everything in the closet, mildew.
They're still flying at Arlington.
They had a big air show down there just last weekend.
Yeah, well, NASA uses it quite a bit, don't they?
Yeah.
No, they have several big air shows down there.
It's not military anymore, but it's the Confederate Air Force does stuff there every year.
I finally got to see the inside of the B-29, the one that's still flying.
We were out.
I don't know how much longer they're going to let that plane fly either.
They got one in England at Duxford.
They've got one up at Bright-Patterson, but it doesn't fly.
They've got one, well, they got the Enola Gay at the Smithsonian.
But you can't crawl around in there.
No, but they let me in this one out here.
Is that because of your husband?
We got out there.
They have quite a display of planes out there.
Oh, yeah, I'm sure.
A lot of it's Navy.
The Navy's back in the facility out there.
That was where the money came from.
We went out there and
It was just about an hour before closing time.
They said, well, if you want to go through the museum, they said it takes you about at least two hours to go through it.
You won't have time.
I said, I don't want to see one plane.
I want to see the B-29.
And so we went out there, and there were three or four mechanics working on it.
I told them what I wanted to do.
They put a ladder up so that we could get in.
I was going to say, because you have to swing up.
Isn't there a little hatch you swing up?
There's a hatch.
And there are some rungs that we used to climb up on, but they put a ladder up.
But the old man.
And Daddy went on up in there.
Was it the first time you were back in a B-29?
Mm-hmm.
Was it the way you remember it?
Oh well they have gutted it primarily.
Oh really?
The gun turret has been taken out.
A lot of the equipment has been...
Updated?
The navigation equipment is obsolete so it's all been taken out and this
positioning system that they have now by satellite.
The GPS thing.
They have that mounted.
The bombardier's section is out, and they have that mounted between the two pilots up where the bombardier would be sitting.
Yeah, a lot of that's probably just extra weight.
They stripped it of all unessential waste.
That makes sense.
Especially where they're flying it.
And they say it still costs them about $5,000 an hour to fly that thing.
Oh, I know.
I know.
Well, not only that, where do you get 120 octane avgas nowadays?
They don't make this stuff.
I don't know what they're flying that thing on.
They're either putting in some sort of super additive, or they've detuned the engines.
So they'll run it.
I know a lot of guys who detune the engines.
these old World War II planes?
Because you can't get really super high octane aviation gas.
It's a problem.
Nobody makes it.
Nobody uses it.
The demand is for jet fuel.
Yeah, that's right.
That's exactly right.
And see, all these little Cessnas and everything else, they're just riding around with low-led whatever or no-led.
I mean, so it's...
It's hard.
It's kind of hard.
I bet you the one in Smithsonian probably looks like what you remember.
Well, now, I understood that all they had was just an old section.
They didn't have the complete plane.
Oh, you may be right.
Now, they're trying to raise...
There's one out in Arizona someplace that there's a group trying to raise money to get it back into flying condition.
Is this the same outfit in that museum in Davis-Monthan?
There's a museum in the desert in California that got started within the last 10 years, maybe.
And they're in the desert on purpose.
It's dry.
Well, that's why they moved Confederate Air Force to Midland, was to get it out of that Harlingen humidity.
The heat doesn't hurt anything, but the humidity's bad.
And there's an Air Force flying museum.
They got started in somewhere out in California, maybe near Muroc, I don't know.
Somewhere out there.
That may be the same bunch.
See, if they're going to fly it, though, it seems to me they would take all the electronics out.
Nobody needs old World War II radios.
Nobody wants World War II navigation systems.
No, the old radar unit, and it was a bulky thing.
We had Loran, which was, I doubt if they even have a Loran transmitting station that will work off the frequencies that they were using back then.
The Loran has been taken out.
Well, that's all gotten real uptown in navigation.
It's quite the deal.
So you all got married when?
August.
That's right, you told me that, August.
And then you had to enter the service again that same month?
Mm-hmm.
What's the mistake?
We went to Biloxi first.
What, you honeymoon to Biloxi?
And there we had the roaches and the ants.
We haven't had a breeze for years.
I had to be true lover.
I never would have made it.
Well, I don't know.
There's worse places in Biloxi.
It's a short list.
Where?
But there are worse places.
San Antonio was nice.
We enjoyed living there.
The only thing I didn't like was when I'd get on the bus to go downtown and everything, all I heard was Spanish.
You know, I thought, they're all talking about me.
You could have learned Spanish and discovered that they weren't.
I know.
But I learned to drive in San Antonio.
That's why I'm such a good driver.
You will.
You will.
That town is, street-wise, is one of the most disorganized towns I've ever been to.
Sure.
They tell me it's built on cow trails.
No, no.
Cows are much more organized than that.
There's a... Well, you got out then in what, 52?
And you came back, you worked for the same contractor here in Dallas?
For a while.
What else did you build, just more buildings?
Then three of us left there and set up our own company, which was kind of short-lived.
You mean the partnership didn't work out, or the economy didn't support it, or what?
Partnership just didn't work out.
One of them was kind of addicted to the bottle.
Makes it sound.
I went then with another company, which I stayed with for 20 some odd years.
Bought into it.
Ended up as one of the major stockholders in the company.
And we were very successful.
It's still going.
I sold out my interest when I retired.
What kind of things did you build?
With them, we built, we specialized in warehouses.
Warehouses and light industrial buildings.
These kind of big butler sort of buildings?
Not butler, but more of the tilt-up wall or masonry walls.
Beams and joist roofs.
You did that in Texas or Southwest?
I did it primarily in Dallas.
We would go to Fort Worth, we went to Arlington, Mid-Cities areas.
We built the building primarily for Trimal Crow.
How do you spell it?
C-R-O-W. Trimal Crow Company.
I'm talking about trammels.
T-R-A-M-M-E-L. T-R-A-M-M-E-L-L. O-E-L-L.
Someone will ask when we're transcribing this, how do you spell it?
He's one of them.
Big developers in the world.
He started spreading out all over the country and wanted us to grow too, but we didn't want to get that.
We wanted something that we could, at the time there were just three of us, something that we could control, keep our,
actual hands-on operation.
We did most of the engineering on the buildings.
We could take it from the ground up.
Not only did the construction, but the engineering.
Worked out very convenient.
Did you use somebody else's
Drawings, you have your own architect?
Trammell Crowe had an architect.
They would give us the layout, the general appearance, and we'd take it from there to get a completed building.
And it worked.
It was a very expeditious type of operations.
We could give him a building.
much shorter than normal development time, building time, where you'd go to an architect, get them to draw a plan to put out for bids and so forth.
We cut that time considerably, which, when you're building on borrowed money and getting a tenant in and so forth is very desirable.
Worked well for him, worked well for us.
Yeah.
Did you use your own?
We used our own labor force and we had some subs that we used.
We had an electrical subcontractor, we had an air conditioning subcontractor, we had a plumbing subcontractor.
The air conditioning and the plumbing subcontractors each we set up in business.
did primarily our work, the electrical contractor was somebody that we had worked with for years.
We worked with those contractors all the way through.
They were in the design and development stage as well as the construction part of it.
They designed the air conditioning part, they designed the electrical work, did the electrical engineering.
And you retired when?
Okay, and you worked with this group for 26 years, you said?
23 years and some odd months.
23, that means.
Well, what were you doing then in between?
See, I'm missing some years here.
You got out of the Air Force in 52.
You went to work for a contractor.
Stayed with him.
17 years, I don't remember.
We just started a partnership.
That was in 50...
Both of them have always been burned when we met one, so that would have been about 57.
So you worked with this other contractor for what, three, four years?
about like that, maybe five.
It must have been about five years before we actually split up, because it was 66 when I went with my friend, Ben Miller.
So your partnership lasted what, three years?
About three years.
So about 1960 that dissolved?
Well, it dissolved in 66.
I went with this other company.
We probably set it up in about 60.
And then you went with this other outfit?
that you worked with for 23 years in 66.
Which is during big growth time in Dallas.
It was.
Through the 80s.
We had more work than we wanted.
We turned work down.
We just couldn't do it.
and gave some of them to other contractors.
I guess the boys are still running it, I don't know.
Haven't kept up with it since our retirement.
Tell me a little bit about your thoughts, your relationship with A&M now.
You were born in 24, this is 96, so you're 72, still young.
I know you've been involved in this travel group, the Aggie.
When did you get started doing that?
86 was our first trip.
86, we took our first trip, and then that was...
a few years after that before we took another one.
But you've been on several of those.
But we've been on several of them now.
Really enjoy traveling with them.
Usually it's with there's someone on the trip that we know or have traveled with before
something of that nature, and it's always nice to be traveling with a congenial group of people.
Sure.
Let me back up, maybe I asked the question wrong.
What I guess I'd like to know is, well it may be obvious to you, it's not necessarily obvious to anyone else,
why you would have an affinity for A&M besides the fact that you graduated?
What I'm trying to get at is why or what were your motivations as you, after you graduated, to stay in touch with the school, to be involved with the school to the degree you have been?
Have you always been involved that way?
Is it something that's happened in the last
I've been involved with the Farmer Students Association probably for the last 25 years or so.
It was just an occasional trip down there before that.
Our son
Our oldest son went to school there and graduated.
He's the one that we lost and who's on our way.
We have this President's Endowment Scholarship plus then this student system endowment in his memory.
It's more or less payback time.
The training and so forth that I got there, the education, the training was what enabled me to be able to do something for them.
In general, I like their
attitude toward making education available at a reasonable cost to people.
I don't think there's anybody that wants to go to get a college education now but
with all the scholarships and assistance that is available at state universities such as A&M that couldn't get an education.
I'm willing to help along those lines as best I can.
Sounds good.
Now a really tough question.
What should I have asked you that I didn't?
That isn't that question.
Because I either didn't know to ask you or...
You've covered just about every subject in this, but I can think of anything you can think to add to it.
I'm just interested in the school.
more from the academic part of it.
Otherwise, I know that a lot of the graduates, there's nothing down there but a football team.
I get really tired of that.
And I have never given or supported the athletic department.
I figure they get enough money to get into enough trouble without me contributing to it.
But there are more beneficial ways that I can put what money I'm able to give to them to use.
Thank you.
Actually, I wish there were more guys like him, frankly.
You're right.
The athletic program, I think, is self-sustaining.
In fact, it seems to be more than self-sustaining in many ways.
But there are certain academic programs, and the library's only one of them.
There are numerous academic programs that go big.
I guess there isn't any reason for that.
It's always refreshingly pleasant to find somebody who is interested.
Three things that I have supported.
That's the Alumni Association, the Corps, and then the library.
So you can't think of anything I should have asked?
I haven't had it in a long time.
Well, I know there's somebody who doesn't have the wit to ask.
Maybe what will happen when I get this transcribed and send it back to you, it might trigger some thoughts or ideas.
Well, I don't know.
We're not real exciting people.
Well, like I said, I'm not necessarily looking for excitement either.
That would be suspicious if all I heard were a series of exciting stories.
I mean, you know what I'm saying?
We're just...
That's not the way real people live.
Everyday citizens.
